# Claude Code workflow reference

Answers the recurring "which command / which flag / which model" questions. If
behavior seems changed, verify with the claude-code-guide agent and update this file.

## Review & cleanup commands

- `/code-review [effort] [instructions]` ‚Äî reviews the **current working diff**.
  Effort: `low`/`medium` (fewer, high-confidence findings), `high`/`max` (broader,
  may include uncertain findings), `ultra` (multi-agent cloud review of the branch,
  billed, user-triggered only; `/ultrareview` is a deprecated alias). Flags:
  `--comment` posts inline PR comments, `--fix` applies findings to the working
  tree. Custom instructions go inline after the effort level.
- `/review <PR#>` ‚Äî reviews a **GitHub pull request** (not the local diff).
- `/simplify` ‚Äî reuse/simplification/efficiency cleanups on changed code, then
  applies them. Quality only; bug-hunting is `/code-review`'s job.
- `/security-review` ‚Äî security review of the branch's pending changes.
- No `/review-branch` exists; `/code-review` on the branch covers it. Extra
  directories come in via `/add-dir` first.

## Verification & running

- `/verify` ‚Äî run the app and observe that a change actually behaves as intended.
- `/run` ‚Äî launch/drive the project app (screenshots, smoke checks).

## Models

- Global model is pinned in settings (`model` key) from the chezmoi repo as
  `{{ .agents.claude.defaults.model }}`; `/model` changes only the current
  session. The pin exists to hold the long-context variant (`[1m]`); it is not
  the top tier.
- `/fast` ‚Äî faster output on the same model, not a smaller one.
- Subagent tiers are relative capability, not fixed model names; the named
  specialists are pinned per tier in `.chezmoidata/agents.yaml`
  (`subagent_tiers.claude`) and do NOT follow `/model`. Only unpinned/built-in
  subagents inherit the session model; a subagent naming an unavailable model
  silently falls back to the inherited one. Tier routing rules live in CLAUDE.md
  (lowest tier likely to one-shot the task).
- Subscription limits (Max plan; last verified 2026-07): a rolling 5-hour session
  window plus TWO weekly buckets ‚Äî all-models, and a separate top-model bucket
  capped at ~50% of the all-models pool. The pinned default draws only the
  all-models bucket; the top model draws the constrained one.
- The top model is escalation-only (hardest long-horizon architecture/synthesis):
  a grown session `/model`-bumped into it meters against the constrained bucket
  every turn ‚Äî the rationale behind the CLAUDE.md intake rule.
- Leaf work on small/mid subagents spares the weekly pool only if those subagents
  actually run the cheap tier.
- If Codex is available, `codex-review` / `second-opinion` are read-only Codex
  consultation for high-risk diffs or stuck calls; Claude and Codex meter on
  independent windows, so read-work can offload to Codex ‚Äî write-work means driving
  the task with Codex yourself. Keep decision ownership in Claude.

## Modes & isolation

- Plan mode is the default (`permissions.defaultMode: "plan"`): read-only until
  the plan is approved. `shift+tab` cycles modes.
- Worktrees isolate parallel work; `worktree.baseRef` is `head` in settings.

## Codex plugin (not installed ‚Äî blocked)

- OpenAI's official plugin (`codex` from `openai/codex-plugin-cc`) is deliberately
  NOT enabled: nested sandboxing is broken on macOS. Codex refuses to start its
  own Seatbelt inside Claude Code's (openai/codex#30615), and `--sandbox
  danger-full-access` panics because CC's sandbox blocks the `configd` lookup its
  HTTP stack needs (anthropics/claude-code#42857). Revisit when #30615 lands or
  `external-sandbox` becomes user-reachable; until then the only workaround is
  sandbox-disabled Bash, which this setup rejects.

